# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: 1-aminoethanol
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:1-aminoethanol/1-aminoethanol] 1-Aminoethanol exists in a solution of acetaldehyde and aqueous ammonia.
[src:1-aminoethanol/1-aminoethanol] 1-Aminoethanol is suggested as intermediate in Strecker reaction of alanine synthesis.
[src:1-aminoethanol/1-aminoethanol] 1-Aminoethanol was first prepared in 1833 by the German chemist Johann Wolfgang Döbereiner; its empirical formula was first determined by the German chemist Justus von Liebig in 1835.
[src:1-aminoethanol/1-aminoethanol] The structure of 1-aminoethanol remained unproven until 1877, when the German-Italian chemist Robert Schiff showed that the structure was CH3CH(OH)NH2.
[src:1-aminoethanol/2-aminoethanol] Ethanolamine is commonly called monoethanolamine or MEA in order to be distinguished from diethanolamine (DEA) and triethanolamine (TEOA).
[src:1-aminoethanol/2-aminoethanol] The ethanolamines comprise a group of amino alcohols.
[src:1-aminoethanol/2-aminoethanol] A class of antihistamines is identified as ethanolamines, which includes carbinoxamine, clemastine, dimenhydrinate, chlorphenoxamine, diphenhydramine and doxylamine.
[src:1-aminoethanol/2-aminoethanol] Ethanolamines, or in particular, their salts, were discovered by Charles Adolphe Wurtz in 1860 by heating 2-chloroethanol with ammonia solution while studying derivatives of ethylene oxide he discovered a year earlier.
[src:1-aminoethanol/2-aminoethanol] He wasn't able to separate the salts or isolate any free bases.
[src:1-aminoethanol/2-aminoethanol] In 1897 Ludwig Knorr developed the modern industrial route (see below) and separated the products, including MEA, by fractional distillation, for the first time studying their properties.
[src:1-aminoethanol/2-aminoethanol] None of the ethanolamines were of any commercial importance until after the WWII industrial production of ethylene oxide took off.
[src:1-aminoethanol/2-aminoethanol] MEA molecules are a component in the formation of cellular membranes and are thus a molecular building block for life.
[src:1-aminoethanol/2-aminoethanol] Ethanolamine is the second-most-abundant head group for phospholipids, substances found in biological membranes (particularly those of prokaryotes); e.g., phosphatidylethanolamine.
[src:1-aminoethanol/2-aminoethanol] It is also used in messenger molecules such as palmitoylethanolamide, which has an effect on CB1 receptors.
[src:1-aminoethanol/2-aminoethanol] MEA was thought to exist only on Earth and on certain asteroids, but in 2021 evidence was found that these molecules exist in interstellar space.
[src:1-aminoethanol/2-aminoethanol] MEA is biodegraded by ethanolamine ammonia-lyase, a B12-dependent enzyme.
[src:1-aminoethanol/2-aminoethanol] It is converted to ammonia and acetaldehyde via initial H-atom abstraction.
[src:1-aminoethanol/2-aminoethanol] Monoethanolamine is produced by treating ethylene oxide with aqueous ammonia; the reaction also produces diethanolamine and triethanolamine.
[src:1-aminoethanol/2-aminoethanol] The ratio of the products can be controlled by the stoichiometry of the reactants.
[src:1-aminoethanol/2-aminoethanol] MEA is used as feedstock in the production of detergents, emulsifiers, polishes, pharmaceuticals, corrosion inhibitors, and chemical intermediates.
[src:1-aminoethanol/2-aminoethanol] For example, reacting ethanolamine with ammonia gives ethylenediamine, a precursor of the commonly used chelating agent, EDTA.
[src:1-aminoethanol/2-aminoethanol] Monoethanolamines can scrub combusted-coal, combusted-methane and combusted-biogas flue emissions of carbon dioxide (CO2) very efficiently.
[src:1-aminoethanol/2-aminoethanol] MEA carbon dioxide scrubbing is also used to regenerate the air on submarines.
[src:1-aminoethanol/2-aminoethanol] Solutions of MEA in water are used as a gas stream scrubbing liquid in amine treaters.
[src:1-aminoethanol/2-aminoethanol] For example, aqueous MEA is used to remove carbon dioxide (CO2) and hydrogen sulfide (H2S) from various gas streams; e.g., flue gas and sour natural gas.
[src:1-aminoethanol/2-aminoethanol] The MEA ionizes dissolved acidic compounds, making them polar and considerably more soluble.
[src:1-aminoethanol/2-aminoethanol] MEA scrubbing solutions can be recycled through a regeneration unit.
[src:1-aminoethanol/2-aminoethanol] When heated, MEA, being a rather weak base, will release dissolved H2S or CO2 gas resulting in a pure MEA solution.
[src:1-aminoethanol/2-aminoethanol] In pharmaceutical formulations, MEA is used primarily for buffering or preparation of emulsions.
[src:1-aminoethanol/2-aminoethanol] MEA can be used as pH regulator in cosmetics.
[src:1-aminoethanol/2-aminoethanol] It is an injectable sclerosant as a treatment option of symptomatic hemorrhoids.
[src:1-aminoethanol/2-aminoethanol] 2–5 ml of ethanolamine oleate can be injected into the mucosa just above the hemorrhoids to cause ulceration and mucosal fixation thus preventing hemorrhoids from descending out of the anal canal.
[src:1-aminoethanol/2-aminoethanol] It is also an ingredient in cleaning fluid for automobile windshields.
[src:1-aminoethanol/2-aminoethanol] Ethanolamine is often used for alkalinization of water in steam cycles of power plants, including nuclear power plants with pressurized water reactors.
[src:1-aminoethanol/2-aminoethanol] This alkalinization is performed to control corrosion of metal components.
[src:1-aminoethanol/2-aminoethanol] ETA (or sometimes a similar organic amine; e.g., morpholine) is selected because it does not accumulate in steam generators (boilers) and crevices due to its volatility, but rather distributes relatively uniformly throughout the entire steam cycle.
[src:1-aminoethanol/2-aminoethanol] In such application, ETA is a key ingredient of so-called "all-volatile treatment" of water (AVT).
[src:1-aminoethanol/alanine] Under biological conditions, alanine exists in its zwitterionic form with its amine group protonated (as −NH+3) and its carboxyl group deprotonated (as −CO−2).
[src:1-aminoethanol/alanine] Alanine is encoded by all codons starting with GC (GCU, GCC, GCA, and GCG).
[src:1-aminoethanol/alanine] The L-isomer of alanine (left-handed) is the one that is incorporated into proteins.
[src:1-aminoethanol/alanine] L-alanine is second only to L-leucine in rate of occurrence, accounting for 7.8% of the primary structure in a sample of 1,150 proteins.
[src:1-aminoethanol/alanine] The right-handed form, D-alanine, occurs in peptides in some bacterial cell walls (in peptidoglycan) and in some peptide antibiotics, and occurs in the tissues of many crustaceans and molluscs as an osmolyte.
[src:1-aminoethanol/alanine] Alanine is not an essential amino acid in humans because it can be synthesized metabolically and does not need to be present in the diet.
[src:1-aminoethanol/alanine] However hypoalaninemia (alanine deficiency) is possible under certain conditions such as ketotic hypoglycemia.
[src:1-aminoethanol/alanine] Alanine was first synthesized in 1850 when Adolph Strecker combined acetaldehyde and ammonia with hydrogen cyanide.
[src:1-aminoethanol/alanine] The amino acid was named *Alanin* in German, in reference to aldehyde, with the interfix *-an-* for ease of pronunciation, the German ending *-in* used in chemical compounds being analogous to English *-ine*.
[src:1-aminoethanol/alanine] Alanine is an aliphatic amino acid, because the side-chain connected to the α-carbon atom is a methyl group (-CH3).
[src:1-aminoethanol/alanine] Alanine is the simplest α-amino acid after glycine.
[src:1-aminoethanol/alanine] The methyl side-chain of alanine is non-reactive and is therefore hardly ever directly involved in protein function.
[src:1-aminoethanol/alanine] Alanine is a nonessential amino acid, meaning it can be manufactured by the human body, and does not need to be obtained through the diet.
[src:1-aminoethanol/alanine] Alanine is found in a wide variety of foods, but is particularly concentrated in meats.
[src:1-aminoethanol/alkanolamine] In organic chemistry, **alkanolamines** (amino alcohols) are organic compounds that contain both hydroxyl (−OH) and amino (−NH2, −NHR, and −NR2) functional groups on an alkane backbone.
[src:1-aminoethanol/alkanolamine] Alkanolamines' bifunctionality and physicochemical characteristics lead to their use in many applications, such as textiles, cosmetics, agricultural chemical intermediates, drugs, and metal working fluids.
[src:1-aminoethanol/alkanolamine] Alkanolamines are present in many approved drugs and thousands of natural products.
[src:1-aminoethanol/alkanolamine] Two amino acids are alkanolamines, formally speaking: serine and hydroxyproline.
[src:1-aminoethanol/alkanolamine] Alkanolamines usually have high-solubility in water due to the hydrogen bonding ability of both the hydroxyl group and the amino group.
[src:1-aminoethanol/alkanolamine] Alkanoamines have also shown a broad toxicity for a variety of organisms, including parasites, insect larvae and eggs, and microbes.
[src:1-aminoethanol/alkanolamine] Studies have also shown that the antimicrobial effect of alkanolamines increases in higher pH's.
[src:1-aminoethanol/alkanolamine] 1-Aminoalcohols are better known as hemiaminals.
[src:1-aminoethanol/alkanolamine] 1-Aminoalcohols tend to be labile, readily converting to more highly condensed derivatives or hydrolyzing to the amine and carbonyl.
[src:1-aminoethanol/alkanolamine] Examples include prolinol (from proline), valinol (from valine), tyrosinol (from tyrosine).
[src:1-aminoethanol/alkanolamine] Some 2-aminoalcohols are produced by the Sharpless asymmetric amino hydroxylation.
[src:1-aminoethanol/alkanolamine] Simple alkanolamines are used as solvents, synthetic intermediates, and high-boiling bases.
[src:1-aminoethanol/alkanolamine] 2-Aminoalcohols have been used as synthetic building blocks and chiral auxiliaries.Amino ethanols have been proven to be vital precursors for chiral morpholines and piperazines.
[src:1-aminoethanol/alkanolamine] Key members: ethanolamine, dimethylethanolamine, *N*-methylethanolamine, Aminomethyl propanol.
[src:1-aminoethanol/alkanolamine] Two popular drugs, often called alkanolamine beta blockers, are members of this structural class: propranolol, pindolol.
[src:1-aminoethanol/alkanolamine] 2-Aminoalcohols can also be found in the direct action subgroup of adrenergic drugs such as epinephrine, isoproterenol, phenylephrine and isoetarine.
[src:1-aminoethanol/alkanolamine] Other medicinally useful derivative of ethanolamine: Isoetarine, veratridine, veratrine, epinephrine (adrenaline), norepinephrine (noradrenaline), atropine.
[src:1-aminoethanol/alkanolamine] Two examples of longer aminoalcohols include Heptaminol, a cardiac stimulant, and propanolamines.
[src:1-aminoethanol/alkanolamine] 1,3-Aminoalcohols are present in several bioactive molecules, such as Sedinone, Dumetorine, and Hygroline.
[src:1-aminoethanol/alkanolamine] 1,3-Aminoalcohols have be synthesize through a couple methods.
[src:1-aminoethanol/alkanolamine] Similar to 2-aminoalcohols, 1,3 aminoalcohols can be formed through ring openings, such as an azo-ring opening and addition.
[src:1-aminoethanol/alkanolamine] 1,3-aminoalcohols can also be synthesized through an azo-aldol condensation or an intermolecular C-H activation.
[src:1-aminoethanol/alkanolamine] 1,4 and 1,5-aminoalcohols have been synthesized through the reduction of cyclic amides.
[src:1-aminoethanol/alkanolamine] Catalyzed alkylation of primary amines with 1,4-butanediol is another synthetic route for 1,4-aminoalcohols.
[src:1-aminoethanol/alkanolamine] Larger amino alcohol (1,5 - and up) synthesis is comparatively underdeveloped.
[src:1-aminoethanol/alkanolamine] Electrochemical ring-openings can produce 1,3 to 1,7-aminoalcohols.
[src:1-aminoethanol/beilstein-journal-of-organic-chemistry] The ***Beilstein Journal of Organic Chemistry*** is a peer-reviewed diamond open-access scientific journal established in 2005.
[src:1-aminoethanol/beilstein-journal-of-organic-chemistry] The journal is published and completely funded by the Beilstein Institute for the Advancement of Chemical Sciences, a German non-profit foundation.
[src:1-aminoethanol/beilstein-journal-of-organic-chemistry] The editor-in-chief is Peter Seeberger (Max Planck Institute of Colloids and Interfaces).
[src:1-aminoethanol/beilstein-journal-of-organic-chemistry] It is a member of the Free Journal Network.
[src:1-aminoethanol/beilstein-journal-of-organic-chemistry] Scientific videos are available for selected articles of the journal.
[src:1-aminoethanol/beilstein-journal-of-organic-chemistry] According to the *Journal Citation Reports*, the journal has a 2023 impact factor of 2.2.
[src:1-aminoethanol/cas-registry-number] This registry includes all substances described since 1957, plus some substances from as far back as the early 1800s.
[src:1-aminoethanol/cas-registry-number] It is a chemical database that includes organic and inorganic compounds, minerals, isotopes, alloys, mixtures, and nonstructurable materials (UVCBs - substances of **u**nknown or **v**ariable composition, **c**omplex reaction products, or **b**iological origin).
[src:1-aminoethanol/cas-registry-number] CAS RNs are generally serial numbers (with a check digit), so they do not contain any information about the structures themselves the way SMILES and InChI strings do.
[src:1-aminoethanol/cas-registry-number] The CAS Registry is an authoritative collection of disclosed chemical substance information.
[src:1-aminoethanol/cas-registry-number] It identifies more than 204 million unique organic and inorganic substances and 69 million protein and DNA sequences, plus additional information about each substance.
[src:1-aminoethanol/cas-registry-number] It is updated with around 15,000 additional new substances daily.
[src:1-aminoethanol/cas-registry-number] The full registry is available on a paid subscription basis.
[src:1-aminoethanol/cas-registry-number] A collection of almost 500 thousand CAS registry numbers is made available under a CC BY-NC license at ACS Commons Chemistry.
[src:1-aminoethanol/cas-registry-number] Historically, chemicals have been identified by a wide variety of synonyms and properties.
[src:1-aminoethanol/cas-registry-number] One of the biggest challenges in the early development of substance indexing, a task undertaken by the Chemical Abstracts Service, was in identifying if a substance in literature was new or if it had been previously discovered.
[src:1-aminoethanol/cas-registry-number] Well-known chemicals may be known via multiple generic, historical, commercial, and/or (black)-market names, and even systematic nomenclature based on structure alone was not universally useful.
[src:1-aminoethanol/cas-registry-number] An algorithm was developed to translate the structural formula of a chemical into a computer-searchable table, which provided a basis for the service that listed each chemical with its CAS Registry Number, the CAS Chemical Registry System, which became operational in 1965.
[src:1-aminoethanol/cas-registry-number] CAS Registry Numbers (CAS RN) are simple and regular, convenient for database searches.
[src:1-aminoethanol/cas-registry-number] They offer a reliable, common and international link to every specific substance across the various nomenclatures and disciplines used by branches of science, industry, and regulatory bodies.
[src:1-aminoethanol/cas-registry-number] Almost all molecule databases today allow searching by CAS Registry Number, and it is used as a global standard.
[src:1-aminoethanol/cas-registry-number] A CAS Registry Number has no inherent meaning, but is assigned in sequential, increasing order when the substance is identified by CAS scientists for inclusion in the CAS Registry database.
[src:1-aminoethanol/cas-registry-number] A CAS RN is separated by hyphens into three parts, the first consisting from two up to seven digits, the second consisting of two digits, and the third consisting of a single digit serving as a check digit.
[src:1-aminoethanol/cas-registry-number] This format gives CAS a maximum capacity of 1,000,000,000 unique numbers.
[src:1-aminoethanol/cas-registry-number] The check digit is found by taking the last digit times 1, the preceding digit times 2, the preceding digit times 3 etc., adding all these up and computing the sum modulo 10.
[src:1-aminoethanol/cas-registry-number] The CAS Registry accepts entries that are (1) descriptive of matter consisting of chemical elements, (2) distinct from existing ones, and (3) present in scientific literature.
[src:1-aminoethanol/cas-registry-number] The definition of "distinct" excludes different phases of the same substance (e.g. water and ice), but includes narrowing of existing concepts (e.g. carbon vs. graphite and diamond; isotope-labelled forms of an existing compound).
[src:1-aminoethanol/cas-registry-number] The Chemical Abstracts Service subscription includes an official search service.
[src:1-aminoethanol/cas-registry-number] The Service ("CAS Data") provides information on the chemical itself, its mentions in published scholarly works and patents, curated biological and chemical reaction data, as well as listings of commercial sources and details on using a substance in a formulation.
[src:1-aminoethanol/cas-registry-number] A subset of the registry can be accessed through the free-of-charge CAS Common Chemistry, which provides identifying information for the chemical in question.
[src:1-aminoethanol/chemical-formula] These are limited to a single typographic line of symbols, which may include subscripts and superscripts.
[src:1-aminoethanol/chemical-formula] A chemical formula is not a chemical name since it does not contain any words.
[src:1-aminoethanol/chemical-formula] Although a chemical formula may imply certain simple chemical structures, it is not the same as a full chemical structural formula.
[src:1-aminoethanol/chemical-formula] Chemical formulae can fully specify the structure of only the simplest of molecules and chemical substances, and are generally more limited in power than chemical names and structural formulae.
[src:1-aminoethanol/chemical-formula] The simplest types of chemical formulae are called *empirical formulae*, which use letters and numbers indicating the numerical *proportions* of atoms of each type.
[src:1-aminoethanol/chemical-formula] **Molecular formulae** indicate the simple numbers of each type of atom in a molecule, with no information on structure.
[src:1-aminoethanol/chemical-formula] For example, the empirical formula for glucose is CH2O (twice as many hydrogen atoms as carbon and oxygen), while its molecular formula is C6H12O6 (12 hydrogen atoms, six carbon and oxygen atoms).
[src:1-aminoethanol/chemical-formula] This is possible if the relevant bonding is easy to show in one dimension.
[src:1-aminoethanol/chemical-formula] An example is the condensed molecular/chemical formula for ethanol, which is CH3−CH2−OH or CH3CH2OH.
[src:1-aminoethanol/chemical-formula] However, even a condensed chemical formula is necessarily limited in its ability to show complex bonding relationships between atoms, especially atoms that have bonds to four or more different substituents.
[src:1-aminoethanol/chemical-formula] For reasons of structural complexity, a single condensed chemical formula (or semi-structural formula) may correspond to different molecules, known as isomers.
[src:1-aminoethanol/chemical-formula] For example, glucose shares its molecular formula C6H12O6 with a number of other sugars, including fructose, galactose and mannose.
[src:1-aminoethanol/chemical-formula] Linear equivalent chemical *names* exist that can and do specify uniquely any complex structural formula (see chemical nomenclature), but such names must use many terms (words), rather than the simple element symbols, numbers, and simple typographical symbols that define a chemical formula.
[src:1-aminoethanol/chemical-formula] Chemical formulae may be used in chemical equations to describe chemical reactions and other chemical transformations, such as the dissolving of ionic compounds into solution.
[src:1-aminoethanol/chemical-formula] A chemical formula identifies each constituent element by its chemical symbol and indicates the proportionate number of atoms of each element.
[src:1-aminoethanol/chemical-formula] In empirical formulae, these proportions begin with a key element and then assign numbers of atoms of the other elements in the compound, by ratios to the key element.
[src:1-aminoethanol/chemical-formula] For molecular compounds, these ratio numbers can all be expressed as whole numbers.
[src:1-aminoethanol/chemical-formula] For example, the empirical formula of ethanol may be written C2H6O because the molecules of ethanol all contain two carbon atoms, six hydrogen atoms, and one oxygen atom.
[src:1-aminoethanol/chemical-formula] Some types of ionic compounds, however, cannot be written with entirely whole-number empirical formulae.
[src:1-aminoethanol/chemical-formula] An example is boron carbide, whose formula of CB*n* is a variable non-whole number ratio with n ranging from over 4 to more than 6.5.
[src:1-aminoethanol/chemical-formula] When the chemical compound of the formula consists of simple molecules, chemical formulae often employ ways to suggest the structure of the molecule.
[src:1-aminoethanol/chemical-formula] These types of formulae are variously known as *molecular formulae* and *condensed formulae*.
[src:1-aminoethanol/chemical-formula] A molecular formula enumerates the number of atoms to reflect those in the molecule, so that the molecular formula for glucose is C6H12O6 rather than the glucose empirical formula, which is CH2O.
[src:1-aminoethanol/chemical-formula] However, except for very simple substances, molecular chemical formulae lack needed structural information, and are ambiguous.
[src:1-aminoethanol/chemical-formula] For simple molecules, a condensed (or semi-structural) formula is a type of chemical formula that may fully imply a correct structural formula.
[src:1-aminoethanol/chemical-formula] For example, ethanol may be represented by the condensed chemical formula CH3CH2OH, and dimethyl ether by the condensed formula CH3OCH3.
[src:1-aminoethanol/chemical-formula] These two molecules have the same empirical and molecular formulae (C2H6O), but may be differentiated by the condensed formulae shown, which are sufficient to represent the full structure of these simple organic compounds.
[src:1-aminoethanol/chemical-formula] Condensed chemical formulae may also be used to represent ionic compounds that do not exist as discrete molecules, but nonetheless do contain covalently bound clusters within them.
[src:1-aminoethanol/chemical-formula] These polyatomic ions are groups of atoms that are covalently bound together and have an overall ionic charge, such as the sulfate [SO4]2− ion.
[src:1-aminoethanol/chemical-formula] Each polyatomic ion in a compound is written individually in order to illustrate the separate groupings.
[src:1-aminoethanol/chemical-formula] For example, the compound dichlorine hexoxide has an empirical formula ClO3, and molecular formula Cl2O6, but in liquid or solid forms, this compound is more correctly shown by an ionic condensed formula [ClO2]+[ClO4]−, which illustrates that this compound consists of [ClO2]+ ions and [ClO4]− ions.
[src:1-aminoethanol/chemical-formula] In such cases, the condensed formula only need be complex enough to show at least one of each ionic species.
[src:1-aminoethanol/chemical-formula] Chemical formulae as described here are distinct from the far more complex chemical systematic names that are used in various systems of chemical nomenclature.
[src:1-aminoethanol/chemical-formula] This name, interpreted by the rules behind it, fully specifies glucose's structural formula, but the name is not a chemical formula as usually understood, and uses terms and words not used in chemical formulae.
[src:1-aminoethanol/chemical-formula] Such names, unlike basic formulae, may be able to represent full structural formulae without graphs.
[src:1-aminoethanol/chemical-formula] In chemistry, the empirical formula of a chemical is a simple expression of the relative number of each type of atom or ratio of the elements in the compound.
[src:1-aminoethanol/chemical-formula] Empirical formulae are the standard for ionic compounds, such as CaCl2, and for macromolecules, such as SiO2.
[src:1-aminoethanol/chemical-formula] An empirical formula makes no reference to isomerism, structure, or absolute number of atoms.
[src:1-aminoethanol/chemical-formula] The term *empirical* refers to the process of elemental analysis, a technique of analytical chemistry used to determine the relative percent composition of a pure chemical substance by element.
[src:1-aminoethanol/chemical-formula] For example, hexane has a molecular formula of C6H14, and (for one of its isomers, n-hexane) a structural formula CH3CH2CH2CH2CH2CH3, implying that it has a chain structure of 6 carbon atoms, and 14 hydrogen atoms.
[src:1-aminoethanol/chemical-formula] However, the empirical formula for hexane is C3H7.
[src:1-aminoethanol/chemical-formula] Likewise the empirical formula for hydrogen peroxide, H2O2, is simply HO, expressing the 1:1 ratio of component elements.
[src:1-aminoethanol/chemical-formula] Formaldehyde and acetic acid have the same empirical formula, CH2O.
[src:1-aminoethanol/chemical-formula] This is also the molecular formula for formaldehyde, but acetic acid has double the number of atoms.
[src:1-aminoethanol/chemical-formula] Like the other formula types detailed below, an empirical formula shows the number of elements in a molecule, and determines whether it is a binary compound, ternary compound, quaternary compound, or has even more elements.
[src:1-aminoethanol/chemical-formula] Molecular formulae simply indicate the numbers of each type of atom in a molecule of a molecular substance.
[src:1-aminoethanol/chemical-formula] They are the same as empirical formulae for molecules that only have one atom of a particular type, but otherwise may have larger numbers.
[src:1-aminoethanol/chemical-formula] An example of the difference is the empirical formula for glucose, which is CH2O (*ratio* 1:2:1), while its molecular formula is C6H12O6 (*number of atoms* 6:12:6).
[src:1-aminoethanol/chemical-formula] A molecular formula provides more information about a molecule than its empirical formula, but is more difficult to establish.
[src:1-aminoethanol/chemical-formula] In addition to indicating the number of atoms of each elementa molecule, a structural formula indicates how the atoms are organized, and shows (or implies) the chemical bonds between the atoms.
[src:1-aminoethanol/chemical-formula] There are multiple types of structural formulas focused on different aspects of the molecular structure.
[src:1-aminoethanol/chemical-formula] The two diagrams show two molecules which are structural isomers of each other, since they both have the same molecular formula C4H10, but they have different structural formulas as shown.
[src:1-aminoethanol/chemical-formula] The connectivity of a molecule often has a strong influence on its physical and chemical properties and behavior.
[src:1-aminoethanol/chemical-formula] Two molecules composed of the same numbers of the same types of atoms (i.e. a pair of isomers) might have completely different chemical and/or physical properties if the atoms are connected differently or in different positions.
[src:1-aminoethanol/chemical-formula] In such cases, a structural formula is useful, as it illustrates which atoms are bonded to which other ones.
[src:1-aminoethanol/chemical-formula] From the connectivity, it is often possible to deduce the approximate shape of the molecule.
[src:1-aminoethanol/chemical-formula] A condensed (or semi-structural) formula may represent the types and spatial arrangement of bonds in a simple chemical substance, though it does not necessarily specify isomers or complex structures.
[src:1-aminoethanol/chemical-formula] For example, ethane consists of two carbon atoms single-bonded to each other, with each carbon atom having three hydrogen atoms bonded to it.
[src:1-aminoethanol/chemical-formula] Its chemical formula can be rendered as CH3CH3.
[src:1-aminoethanol/chemical-formula] In ethylene there is a double bond between the carbon atoms (and thus each carbon only has two hydrogens), therefore the chemical formula may be written: CH2CH2, and the fact that there is a double bond between the carbons is implicit because carbon has a valence of four.
[src:1-aminoethanol/chemical-formula] However, a more explicit method is to write H2C=CH2 or less commonly H2C::CH2.
[src:1-aminoethanol/chemical-formula] The two lines (or two pairs of dots) indicate that a double bond connects the atoms on either side of them.
[src:1-aminoethanol/chemical-formula] A triple bond may be expressed with three lines (HC≡CH) or three pairs of dots (HC:::CH), and if there may be ambiguity, a single line or pair of dots may be used to indicate a single bond.
[src:1-aminoethanol/chemical-formula] Molecules with multiple functional groups that are the same may be expressed by enclosing the repeated group in round brackets.
[src:1-aminoethanol/chemical-formula] For example, isobutane may be written (CH3)3CH.
[src:1-aminoethanol/chemical-formula] This condensed structural formula implies a different connectivity from other molecules that can be formed using the same atoms in the same proportions (isomers).
[src:1-aminoethanol/chemical-formula] The formula (CH3)3CH implies a central carbon atom connected to one hydrogen atom and three methyl groups (CH3).
[src:1-aminoethanol/chemical-formula] The same number of atoms of each element (10 hydrogens and 4 carbons, or C4H10) may be used to make a straight chain molecule, *n*-butane: CH3CH2CH2CH3.
[src:1-aminoethanol/chemical-formula] The International Union of Crystallography (IUCr) has proposed a crystal-chemical formula notation that extends standard formulae with optional annotations for these items.
[src:1-aminoethanol/chemical-formula] The alkene called but-2-ene has two isomers, which the chemical formula CH3CH=CHCH3 does not identify.
[src:1-aminoethanol/chemical-formula] The relative position of the two methyl groups must be indicated by additional notation denoting whether the methyl groups are on the same side of the double bond (*cis* or *Z*) or on the opposite sides from each other (*trans* or *E*).
[src:1-aminoethanol/chemical-formula] As noted above, in order to represent the full structural formulae of many complex organic and inorganic compounds, chemical nomenclature may be needed which goes well beyond the available resources used above in simple condensed formulae.
[src:1-aminoethanol/chemical-formula] See IUPAC nomenclature of organic chemistry and IUPAC nomenclature of inorganic chemistry 2005 for examples.
[src:1-aminoethanol/chemical-formula] In addition, linear naming systems such as International Chemical Identifier (InChI) allow a computer to construct a structural formula, and simplified molecular-input line-entry system (SMILES) allows a more human-readable ASCII input.
[src:1-aminoethanol/chemical-formula] However, all these nomenclature systems go beyond the standards of chemical formulae, and technically are chemical naming systems, not formula systems.
[src:1-aminoethanol/chemical-formula] For polymers in condensed chemical formulae, parentheses are placed around the repeating unit.
[src:1-aminoethanol/chemical-formula] For example, a hydrocarbon molecule that is described as CH3(CH2)50CH3, is a molecule with fifty repeating units.
[src:1-aminoethanol/chemical-formula] If the number of repeating units is unknown or variable, the letter *n* may be used to indicate this formula: CH3(CH2)*n*CH3.
[src:1-aminoethanol/chemical-formula] For ions, the charge on a particular atom may be denoted with a right-hand superscript.
[src:1-aminoethanol/chemical-formula] The total charge on a charged molecule or a polyatomic ion may also be shown in this way, such as for hydronium, H3O+, or sulfate, SO2−4.
[src:1-aminoethanol/chemical-formula] Here + and − are used in place of +1 and −1, respectively.
[src:1-aminoethanol/chemical-formula] For more complex ions, brackets [ ] are often used to enclose the ionic formula, as in [B12H12]2−, which is found in compounds such as caesium dodecaborate, Cs2[B12H12].
[src:1-aminoethanol/chemical-formula] Parentheses ( ) can be nested inside brackets to indicate a repeating unit, as in Hexamminecobalt(III) chloride, [Co(NH3)6]3+Cl−3.
[src:1-aminoethanol/chemical-formula] Here, (NH3)6 indicates that the ion contains six ammine groups (NH3) bonded to cobalt, and [ ] encloses the entire formula of the ion with charge +3.
[src:1-aminoethanol/chemical-formula] This is strictly optional; a chemical formula is valid with or without ionization information, and Hexamminecobalt(III) chloride may be written as [Co(NH3)6]3+Cl−3 or [Co(NH3)6]Cl3.
[src:1-aminoethanol/chemical-formula] Brackets, like parentheses, behave in chemistry as they do in mathematics, grouping terms together – they are not specifically employed only for ionization states.
[src:1-aminoethanol/chemical-formula] In the latter case here, the parentheses indicate 6 groups all of the same shape, bonded to another group of size 1 (the cobalt atom), and then the entire bundle, as a group, is bonded to 3 chlorine atoms.
[src:1-aminoethanol/chemical-formula] In the former case, it is clearer that the bond connecting the chlorines is ionic, rather than covalent.
[src:1-aminoethanol/chemical-formula] Although isotopes are more relevant to nuclear chemistry or stable isotope chemistry than to conventional chemistry, different isotopes may be indicated with a prefixed superscript in a chemical formula.
[src:1-aminoethanol/chemical-formula] For example, the phosphate ion containing radioactive phosphorus-32 is [32PO4]3−.
[src:1-aminoethanol/chemical-formula] Also a study involving stable isotope ratios might include the molecule 18O16O.
[src:1-aminoethanol/chemical-formula] A left-hand subscript is sometimes used redundantly to indicate the atomic number.
[src:1-aminoethanol/chemical-formula] For example, 8O2 for dioxygen, and 16 8O 2 for the most abundant isotopic species of dioxygen.
[src:1-aminoethanol/chemical-formula] This is convenient when writing equations for nuclear reactions, in order to show the balance of charge more clearly.
[src:1-aminoethanol/chemical-formula] The @ symbol (at sign) indicates an atom or molecule trapped inside a cage but not chemically bound to it.
[src:1-aminoethanol/chemical-formula] For example, a buckminsterfullerene (C60) with an atom (M) would simply be represented as MC60 regardless of whether M was inside the fullerene without chemical bonding or outside, bound to one of the carbon atoms.
[src:1-aminoethanol/chemical-formula] Using the @ symbol, this would be denoted M@C60 if M was inside the carbon network.
[src:1-aminoethanol/chemical-formula] A non-fullerene example is [As@Ni12As20]3−, an ion in which one arsenic (As) atom is trapped in a cage formed by the other 32 atoms.
[src:1-aminoethanol/chemical-formula] This notation was proposed in 1991 with the discovery of fullerene cages (endohedral fullerenes), which can trap atoms such as La to form, for example, La@C60 or La@C82.
[src:1-aminoethanol/chemical-formula] The choice of the symbol has been explained by the authors as being concise, readily printed and transmitted electronically (the at sign is included in ASCII, which most modern character encoding schemes are based on), and the visual aspects suggesting the structure of an endohedral fullerene.
[src:1-aminoethanol/chemical-formula] Chemical formulae most often use integers for each element.
[src:1-aminoethanol/chemical-formula] However, there is a class of compounds, called non-stoichiometric compounds, that cannot be represented by small integers.
[src:1-aminoethanol/chemical-formula] Such a formula might be written using decimal fractions, as in Fe0.95O, or it might include a variable part represented by a letter, as in Fe1−*x*O, where *x* is normally much less than 1.
[src:1-aminoethanol/chemical-formula] A chemical formula used for a series of compounds that differ from each other by a constant unit is called a *general formula*.
[src:1-aminoethanol/chemical-formula] It generates a homologous series of chemical formulae.
[src:1-aminoethanol/chemical-formula] For example, alcohols may be represented by the formula C*n*H2*n* + 1OH (*n* ≥ 1), giving the homologs methanol, ethanol, propanol for 1 ≤ *n* ≤ 3.
[src:1-aminoethanol/chemical-formula] When the formula contains no carbon, all the elements, including hydrogen, are listed alphabetically.
[src:1-aminoethanol/chemical-formula] The Hill system was first published by Edwin A.
[src:1-aminoethanol/chemical-formula] Hill of the United States Patent and Trademark Office in 1900.
[src:1-aminoethanol/chemical-formula] It is the most commonly used system in chemical databases and printed indexes to sort lists of compounds.
[src:1-aminoethanol/chemical-formula] A list of formulae in Hill system order is arranged alphabetically, as above, with single-letter elements coming before two-letter symbols when the symbols begin with the same letter (so "B" comes before "Be", which comes before "Br").
[src:1-aminoethanol/comptox-chemicals-dashboard] The **CompTox Chemicals Dashboard** is a freely accessible online database created and maintained by the U.S.
[src:1-aminoethanol/comptox-chemicals-dashboard] The database provides access to multiple types of data including physicochemical properties, environmental fate and transport, exposure, usage, *in vivo* toxicity, and *in vitro* bioassay.
[src:1-aminoethanol/comptox-chemicals-dashboard] EPA and other scientists use the data and models contained within the dashboard to help identify chemicals that require further testing and reduce the use of animals in chemical testing.
[src:1-aminoethanol/comptox-chemicals-dashboard] The Dashboard is also used to provide public access to information from EPA Action Plans, e.g. around perfluorinated alkylated substances.
[src:1-aminoethanol/comptox-chemicals-dashboard] Originally titled the Chemistry Dashboard, the first version was released in 2016.
[src:1-aminoethanol/comptox-chemicals-dashboard] The latest release of the database (version 3.0.5) contains manually curated data for over 875,000 chemicals and incorporates the latest data generated from the EPA's Toxicity Forecaster (ToxCast) high-throughput screening program.
[src:1-aminoethanol/comptox-chemicals-dashboard] The Chemicals Dashboard incorporates data from several previous EPA databases into one package including the ToxCast Dashboard, the Endocrine Disruption Screening Program (EDSP) Dashboard and the Chemical and Products Database (CPDat).
[src:1-aminoethanol/comptox-chemicals-dashboard] The CompTox Chemicals Dashboard database contains high quality chemical structures and information that have been extensively curated and quality checked, which can be used as a resource for analytical scientists involved in structure identification.
[src:1-aminoethanol/comptox-chemicals-dashboard] Chemical hazard data in the dashboard comes from both traditional laboratory animal studies and high-throughput screening.
[src:1-aminoethanol/comptox-chemicals-dashboard] Biological data from high-throughput screening is generated by EPA's ToxCast program, the ToxCast data in the database provides information about the assays used and their response potency and efficacy.
[src:1-aminoethanol/comptox-chemicals-dashboard] These data can be found in the bioactivity tab.
[src:1-aminoethanol/comptox-chemicals-dashboard] The Chemicals Dashboard can be accessed via a web interface or sets of data within it can be downloaded for use offline.
[src:1-aminoethanol/comptox-chemicals-dashboard] The Lists tab can be used to browse and download groups of related chemicals based on their relevance to a specific research topic (such as additives in cigarettes or chemicals demonstrating effects on neurodevelopmental effects) or the specific assay endpoints they are covered by.
[src:1-aminoethanol/comptox-chemicals-dashboard] Within the online dashboard searches can be performed by product/use categories, assay/gene, systematic name, synonym, CAS number, DSSTox Substance ID or InChiKey.
[src:1-aminoethanol/comptox-chemicals-dashboard] Under the Advanced Search tab chemicals can be searched based on their mass or molecular formula.
[src:1-aminoethanol/comptox-chemicals-dashboard] Searches can also be performed for groups of chemicals based on Chemical Name CASRN, InChIKey, DSSTox Substance ID, DSSTox Compound ID, InChIKey Skeleton, MS-Ready Formula, Exact Formula, or Monoisotopic Mass using the batch search function.
[src:1-aminoethanol/comptox-chemicals-dashboard] An automated read-across tool called Generalized Read-Across (GenRA) is integrated into The Chemicals Dashboard.
[src:1-aminoethanol/comptox-chemicals-dashboard] GenRA is designed to keep the expert consideration inherent in the read-across method, but automate the chemical selection process to help predict toxicity.
[src:1-aminoethanol/comptox-chemicals-dashboard] The Dashboard also has the capability to search existing scientific literature sources such as PubMed, via a web-based version of the "Abstract Sifter", Google Scholar and reports from EPA's Provisional Peer Reviewed Toxicity Values (PPRTV) and the EPA Integrated Risk Information System (IRIS).
[src:1-aminoethanol/comptox-chemicals-dashboard] Real-time QSAR prediction for multiple physicochemical property and toxicity endpoints is available through the predictions tab.
[src:1-aminoethanol/comptox-chemicals-dashboard] The dashboard provides support for mass spectrometry providing searches against the chemical data contained in the database based on mass and molecular formula.
[src:1-aminoethanol/comptox-chemicals-dashboard] The dashboard has been applied to non-targeted analysis searching for "known unknowns".
[src:1-aminoethanol/comptox-chemicals-dashboard] Both targeted mass spectrometry and non-targeted mass spectrometry are supported.
[src:1-aminoethanol/comptox-chemicals-dashboard] The searches utilize a search based on "MS-Ready" forms of chemical compounds.
[src:1-aminoethanol/comptox-chemicals-dashboard] Individual chemical substances are collapsed into a form that would be detected by mass spectrometry such that salts are desalted and neutralized and multi-component chemicals are separated into their individual components.
